Note: An empty alt="" tells screen readers to skip the image entirely, which is appropriate only for decorative images that add no information.","aiPriority":7},{"issueId":"ba58737e-5ef0-471f-aba1-c8d277247326","aiExplanation":"This link contains only an icon with no text alternative, making it completely inaccessible to screen reader users. When a screen reader encounters this link, it will announce something like 'link' with no indication of where the link goes or what action it performs. Users navigating by keyboard who rely on screen readers will not know the purpose of this interactive element, potentially missing important functionality or navigation options.","aiFixSuggestion":"Add accessible text to the link using one of these methods:

Option 1 - aria-label (best for icon-only buttons):
Before:
<a href="/page"><i class="icon"></i></a>

After:
<a href="/page" aria-label="Go to page name"><i class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></i></a>

Option 2 - Visually hidden text (good for SEO and accessibility):
<a href="/page">
  <i class="icon" aria-hidden="true"></i>
  <span class="sr-only">Go to page name</span>
</a>

CSS for visually hidden text:
.sr-only {
  position: absolute;
  width: 1px;
  height: 1px;
  padding: 0;
  margin: -1px;
  overflow: hidden;
  clip: rect(0, 0, 0, 0);
  white-space: nowrap;
  border: 0;
}

Note: Adding aria-hidden="true" to the icon prevents screen readers from announcing the icon character or font name.","aiPriority":6}]

[{"issueId":"cf92bfc8-e02a-4e91-aaaf-a7bef79b0340","aiExplanation":"This text has insufficient color contrast between the foreground text and its background. The current ratio is 3.5:1, but WCAG AA requires at least 4.5:1 for normal text. Users with low vision, aging eyes, or color blindness may struggle to read this content or may not see it at all. This affects a significant portion of users - approximately 8% of men have some form of color vision deficiency, and many more users experience situational impairments like screen glare or poor lighting conditions.","aiFixSuggestion":"Increase the color contrast to meet the minimum 4.5:1 ratio for normal-sized text. You can either darken the text color or lighten the background color.

Before:
<p class="low-contrast">Sample text with low contrast</p>

Option 1 - Darken the text:
<p class="low-contrast" style="color: #595959;">Sample text with low contrast</p>

Option 2 - Update your CSS:
.low-contrast {
  color: #595959; /* Darker shade that provides 4.5:1+ contrast */
}

Use a contrast checker tool like WebAIM's Contrast Checker (https://webaim.org/resources/contrastchecker/) to verify your new color combination meets the 4.5:1 minimum ratio. For large text (18pt+ or 14pt+ bold), the minimum ratio is 3:1.","aiPriority":8},{"issueId":"eec7c0ae-3667-4873-bb68-2ed3c6d2e972","aiExplanation":"This image is missing an alt attribute, which means screen reader users have no way to know what the image represents. When a screen reader encounters an image without alt text, it typically announces the filename (in this case 'logo.png'), which provides no useful information. Since this appears to be a logo, it likely conveys brand identity or may serve as a link to the homepage. Without proper alt text, blind users and those using text-only browsers miss this information entirely.","aiFixSuggestion":"Add an alt attribute that describes the image's purpose. For a logo, include the organization name and its function.

Before:
<img src="logo.png">

After (if the logo is informative):
